,1710,1753,1766,1821,1834,1847,1929,2903,4332,4818 'x64':4292,4778 'x86':2630 'xarg':3320,3362,3368,3377 'xr':1403,1499,1512,1525,1538,1551,1577,1608,1697,1709,1752,1765,1820,1833,1846,1928,2902 'y':2393,2410 'yes':2411,3608,3620,4174,4180 'yılmaz':4124,4711 'z':258,1473,5320,5323 'z-a':1472 'zsh':220,257,602 'zshrc':569,603 'öz':4126,4714
2	3	TP Linux	Study linux commands	Linux	f	C:\\xampp\\htdocs\\Public_library_codebase\\storage\\uploads\\documents\\3\\e6f2c68833d53a8662b1cf1caa3a37b0.pdf	\N	2026-04-14 13:58:38.81055	Linux Shell\r\nWhat is a Shell and Why Do We Need It?\r\nComputer hardware (CPU, RAM, Disk) is useless on its own. We need a Kernel to manage them.\r\nHowever, the kernel is also a complex structure that only understands 0s and 1s. This is where the\r\nShell comes in.\r\nThe Shell's Job: It translates the "near-human language" commands you type (e.g.,\r\nls\r\n- list) into "machine language" that the kernel can understand. After the kernel performs the\r\noperation, the shell takes the result and prints it back to the screen in a way you can understand.\r\nIn a way, it acts as a translator.\r\nThere are two main types of shells in Linux: Command Line (CLI) and Graphical Interface\r\n(GUI).\r\n\r\nCommand Line (CLI)\r\nThe command line is a text-based communication method. You open a window called\r\nTerminal\r\nand manage the computer by typing commands.\r\n\r\n\f\fWhy Should I Use Command Line?\r\n•\r\n•\r\n•\r\n\r\nSpeed: Copying files, installing programs is much faster with the keyboard.\r\nAutomation: You can do hundreds of operations with a single command file (script).\r\nRemote Access: When you connect to servers with SSH, there is no graphical interface,\r\nonly the command line.\r\n\r\nGraphical Interface (GUI)\r\nIt is an interface managed with windows, icons, and mouse, just like in Windows or macOS.\r\n\r\n\f\fShell Types (Bash, Zsh, Fish)\r\nThere is not a single shell in Linux. You can change it according to your needs.\r\n1. Bash (Bourne Again Shell): The most common and standard shell. Comes by default in\r\nmost Linux distributions.\r\n2. Zsh (Z Shell): Compatible with Bash but offers more advanced auto-completion and\r\ntheme support (macOS default).\r\n3. Fish: User-friendly, colors commands as you type and offers suggestions.\r\nTo find out which shell you are using:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ echo $SHELL\r\n/bin/bash\r\n\r\nIn the above output, we see that the system returned the path\r\n/bin/bash\r\nas a response. This means we are currently actively using the Bash shell.\r\n\r\nWhat is a Terminal?\r\nThe terminal application acts as a gateway allowing users to interact with the shell, offering a\r\ntext-based interface where commands can be entered and their outputs seen.\r\n\r\n\f\fUseful Terminal Commands:\r\n1. clear\r\n(Clear Screen): Used to clean the terminal screen when it gets filled with commands.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ clear\r\n\r\nWhen you run this command, all previous outputs are cleared and the cursor moves to the\r\ntop line. It's like opening a clean page.\r\n2. history\r\n(Past Commands): Gives a list of commands you ran before. Great for finding a\r\ncommand you forgot.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ history\r\n1 ls\r\n2 cd Documents\r\n3 pwd\r\n4 ping google.com\r\n5 cat /etc/passwd\r\n6 clear\r\n7 whoami\r\n8 sudo apt update\r\n9 exit\r\n10 history\r\n\r\nIn the output, the numbers on the left show the sequence number of the command. For\r\nexample, if you type\r\n!4\r\nand press enter, it will re-run the 4th command\r\nping google.com\r\n.\r\n3. type\r\n(Command Type): Shows what a command really is (alias, builtin, file).\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ type ls\r\nls is aliased to `ls --color=auto'\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ type cd\r\ncd is a shell builtin\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ type grep\r\ngrep is /usr/bin/grep\r\n\r\n\fHere we understand that the\r\nls\r\ncommand is actually an alias (alias) to give colored output, the\r\ncd\r\ncommand is built into the shell (builtin), and the\r\ngrep\r\ncommand is a real program sitting on the disk.\r\n\r\nShell Configuration Files (\r\n.bashrc\r\n,\r\n.zshrc\r\n)\r\nEvery time the terminal opens, the shell reads some hidden settings files in your home directory (\r\n/home/user\r\n). You can add your own shortcuts to these files.\r\n•\r\n\r\nIf using Bash:\r\n.bashrc\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\nIf using Zsh:\r\n.zshrc\r\n\r\nExample Scenario: We want to clear the screen by typing just\r\nc\r\ninstead of\r\nclear\r\nevery time.\r\n1. Open the file with nano editor:\r\n\r\n\fnano ~/.bashrc\r\n2. Add this line to the bottom:\r\nalias c='clear'\r\n3. Save and exit (\r\nCTRL+O\r\n,\r\nEnter\r\n,\r\nCTRL+X\r\n).\r\n4. Load settings:\r\nsource ~/.bashrc\r\nNow let's type\r\nc\r\nin the terminal:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ c\r\n\r\nThe command will work and the screen will be cleared. With this method you can shorten long\r\nand complex commands.\r\n\r\nEnvironment Variables\r\nDynamic values that affect how the operating system and programs work.\r\nMost Important Variables:\r\nVariable Description\r\n$HOME User's home directory.\r\n$USER Current username.\r\n$PWD Present Working Directory.\r\n$SHELL Shell program used.\r\n$PATH List of directories where commands are searched.\r\n\r\n\fPractical Example: Viewing Variables\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ echo $HOME\r\n/home/user\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ echo $USER\r\nuser\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ echo $PWD\r\n/home/user/Desktop\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ printenv PATH\r\n/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin\r\n\r\nThe\r\necho\r\ncommand prints the value of the variable to the screen. In the\r\n$PATH\r\noutput, you see directory paths separated by colons (:). When you type a command, Linux looks\r\nin these directories in order.\r\n\r\nCommand Chaining Operators\r\nSpecial characters are used to write multiple commands on a single line.\r\n1. Sequential Execution (\r\n;\r\n)\r\nThe first command finishes, even if it errors, the second one runs.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ echo "First Command" ; date\r\nFirst Command\r\nFri Oct 20 14:30:00 UTC 2023\r\n\r\nThe first command printed text, immediately after the\r\ndate\r\ncommand ran and showed the date.\r\n2. Continue if Successful (\r\n&&\r\n)\r\nIf the first command is successful (doesn't error), the second one runs.\r\n\r\n\fuser@hackerbox:~$ mkdir test_directory && cd test_directory\r\nuser@hackerbox:~/test_directory$ pwd\r\n/home/user/test_directory\r\n\r\nHere since\r\nmkdir\r\nwas successful, the\r\ncd\r\ncommand ran and we entered the new directory.\r\n3. Run if Error (\r\n||\r\n)\r\nIf the first command errors, the second one runs. Usually used to show error messages.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ cd nonexistent_directory || echo "No such directory!"\r\n-bash: cd: nonexistent_directory: No such file or directory\r\nNo such directory!\r\n\r\nSince the\r\ncd\r\ncommand couldn't find the directory and errored, the\r\n||\r\noperator kicked in and ran the\r\necho\r\ncommand.\r\n\r\nScript Start (Shebang\r\n#!\r\n)\r\nTo specify that a text file is a shell script, Shebang (\r\n#!\r\n) is added to the first line.\r\n#!/bin/bash\r\necho "Hello World"\r\n\r\nThis line tells the system "Run this file using the /bin/bash program".\r\n\r\n\fNavigation in Directories\r\nIn a typical graphical interface (desktop environment), you can browse directories using a mouse,\r\nbut on the Linux terminal, you need to use various commands to navigate, interact with files, and\r\ndirectories.\r\nThis section is designed to teach the basics of Linux navigation, including navigating directories,\r\nlisting files, managing files, and using shortcuts for efficiency.\r\n\r\nWhat is a Directory and Path?\r\nIn Linux, everything is a file, and these files are organized inside directories called Directories.\r\n•\r\n\r\nRoot Directory (/): The starting point of the entire system. Like\r\nC:\\\r\nin Windows, but Linux has a single root.\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\nPath: The address of a file.\r\no Absolute Path: Starting the address description from the very beginning (\r\n/\r\n). E.g.,\r\n/home/john/pictures/holiday.jpg\r\no\r\n\r\nRelative Path: Starting the address description from "where I am currently". E.g.,\r\npictures/holiday.jpg\r\n\r\n1. Where Am I? (\r\npwd\r\n)\r\nThe\r\npwd\r\n(Print Working Directory) command shows where you are currently in the file system.\r\n\r\n\fUsage:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ pwd\r\n/home/user\r\n\r\nThis command means, "You are currently inside the\r\n/home/user\r\ndirectory."\r\nOther Useful Commands:\r\n•\r\n\r\nrealpath\r\n: Shows the full (absolute) path of a file.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ realpath notes.txt\r\n/home/user/notes.txt\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\nbasename\r\n: Returns only the file name from the path.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ basename /home/user/notes.txt\r\nnotes.txt\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\ndirname\r\n: Returns only the directory part of the path.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ dirname /home/user/notes.txt\r\n/home/user\r\n\r\n2. Changing Directory (\r\ncd\r\n)\r\nSwitch between directories with the\r\ncd\r\n(Change Directory) command.\r\nCommand Description\r\nExample Output (Effect)\r\ncd [directory] Enters the specified directory. Moves user to the specified directory.\r\ncd /full/path Goes with absolute path.\r\nMoves user to the directory at full path.\r\n\r\n\fCommand\r\ncd ..\r\n\r\ncd ~\r\n\r\ncd -\r\n\r\nDescription\r\n\r\nExample Output (Effect)\r\n/home/user/Downloads\r\nGoes up one directory.\r\n->\r\n/home/user\r\n/var/www\r\nReturns to home directory.\r\n->\r\n/home/user\r\n/etc\r\nReturns to previous location. ->\r\n/var/www\r\n\r\nPractical Examples:\r\n1. Going Up One Directory (\r\ncd ..\r\n):\r\nuser@hackerbox:/var/www$ cd ..\r\nuser@hackerbox:/var$\r\n\r\nWe went up from the\r\n/var/www\r\ndirectory to the\r\n/var\r\ndirectory.\r\n2. Returning to Home Directory (\r\ncd ~\r\n):\r\nuser@hackerbox:/var/log$ cd ~\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$\r\n\r\nWherever you are, it teleports you to your home directory\r\n/home/username\r\n.\r\n\r\n\f3. Returning to Previous Directory (\r\ncd ):\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ cd /etc\r\nuser@hackerbox:/etc$ cd /home/user\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$\r\n\r\nFirst we went to the\r\n/etc\r\ndirectory, then by saying\r\ncd we returned to where we came from.\r\n\r\n3. Listing (\r\nls\r\n)\r\nThe\r\nls\r\n(List) command shows the contents of a directory. Used alone, it gives little information, so it is\r\nused with parameters (flags).\r\nFrequently Used Parameters Table:\r\nParameter Description\r\nExample Output\r\nLong List: Shows permissions, owner, size, and date in drwxr-xr-x 2 user user\r\n-l\r\ndetail.\r\n4096 ...\r\nAll: Shows hidden files (starting with\r\n-a\r\n.\r\n.bashrc .profile .\r\n).\r\n4.0K\r\n-h\r\nHuman: Shows file size in KB, MB instead of Bytes. ,\r\n23M\r\n-t\r\nTime: Sorts files by modification date (newest first).\r\n(Date-sorted list)\r\n\r\n\fParameter Description\r\n-r\r\nReverse: Reverses the sort order.\r\n-R\r\nRecursive: Lists inside subdirectories too.\r\n-S\r\nSize: Sorts files by size (Largest to smallest).\r\n\r\nExample Output\r\n(Z-A sorted list)\r\n(Whole directory tree)\r\n(Size-sorted list)\r\n\r\nExample Scenario 1: Detailed Listing (\r\nls -l\r\n)\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -l\r\ntotal 16\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user users 4096 Jul 29 08:24 Desktop\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user users 4096 Jul 29 08:24 Documents\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user users 4096 Jul 29 08:24 Downloads\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user users 4096 Jul 29 08:24 Pictures\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user users 4096 Jul 29 08:24 Videos\r\n-rw-r--r-- 1 user users 2100 Aug 01 12:00 notes.txt\r\n-rwxr-xr-x 1 user users 500 Aug 01 11:00 script.sh\r\n\r\nIn the output obtained with the\r\n-l\r\nparameter, we see columns with the following structure:\r\nColumn content Description\r\ndrwxr-xr-x\r\nFile type and permissions (d: directory, -: file, rwx: permissions)\r\n2\r\nNumber of hard links to the file/directory\r\nuser\r\nThe user who owns the file/directory\r\nusers\r\nThe group who owns the file/directory\r\n4096\r\nFile size (Bytes)\r\nJul 29 08:24\r\nDate of creation or last modification of file/directory\r\nDesktop\r\nName of the file/directory\r\nHere we see that\r\nDesktop\r\nand\r\nDocuments\r\nare directories (\r\nd\r\n), others are files (\r\n), along with their sizes and dates.\r\nExample Scenario 2: Seeing Hidden Files (\r\n\r\n\fls -la\r\n)\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -la\r\ntotal 32\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 5 user user 4096 Oct 20 10:00 .\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 3 root root 4096 Oct 20 09:00 ..\r\n-rw------- 1 user user 220 Oct 20 09:00 .bash_logout\r\n-rw------- 1 user user 3771 Oct 20 09:00 .bashrc\r\n-rw------- 1 user user 807 Oct 20 09:00 .profile\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user user 4096 Oct 20 10:00 Documents\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user user 4096 Oct 20 10:00 Downloads\r\n\r\nNormally hidden configuration files like\r\n.bashrc\r\nappeared.\r\n.\r\n(current directory) and\r\n..\r\n(parent directory) are also listed.\r\nExample Scenario 3: Sorting by Time (\r\nls -lt\r\n)\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -lt\r\ntotal 16\r\n-rw-r--r-- 1 user user 2100 Oct 20 12:00 notes.txt\r\n-rwxr-xr-x 1 user user 500 Oct 20 11:00 script.sh\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user user 4096 Oct 20 10:00 Documents\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user user 4096 Oct 20 10:00 Downloads\r\n\r\nThe most recently modified file (\r\nnotes.txt\r\n) appears at the top.\r\nExample Scenario 4: Listing All Subdirectories (\r\nls -R\r\n)\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -R\r\n.:\r\nDocuments Downloads notes.txt\r\n./Documents:\r\nReport.pdf Picture.jpg\r\n./Downloads:\r\ninstaller.zip\r\n\r\n\fNot only listed our current directory, but also dumped the contents of its subdirectories.\r\nExample Scenario 5: Sorting by Size (\r\nls -lS\r\n)\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -lS\r\n-rw-r--r-- 1 user user 10485760 Oct 20 12:00 large_file.iso\r\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 user user\r\n4096 Oct 20 10:00 Documents\r\n-rw-r--r-- 1 user user\r\n2100 Oct 20 12:00 notes.txt\r\n\r\nThe largest file (\r\nlarge_file.iso\r\n) is at the top.\r\n\r\n4. Directory Stack (\r\npushd\r\nand\r\npopd\r\n)\r\nSometimes you need to temporarily check another place while working in a directory and come\r\nback.\r\nUsage:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~/project$ pushd /var/log\r\n/var/log ~/project\r\nuser@hackerbox:/var/log$ popd\r\n~/project\r\nuser@hackerbox:~/project$\r\n\r\nWith\r\npushd\r\nwe teleported to\r\n/var/log\r\nbut threw our old location into memory. When we said\r\npopd\r\n, we returned exactly to where we left off (\r\n~/project\r\n).\r\n\r\n\f5. Tree View (\r\ntree\r\n)\r\nVisualizes the directory structure like a tree branch.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ tree -L 2\r\n.\r\n├── Desktop\r\n├── Documents\r\n│\r\n├── Work\r\n│\r\n│\r\n└── ProjectA\r\n│\r\n└── Personal\r\n│\r\n└── Photos\r\n└── Downloads\r\n└── installer.zip\r\n\r\nAllows us to understand the nested structure of directories at a glance. The\r\n-L 2\r\nparameter tells it to only go 2 levels deep.\r\n\r\nFile and Directory Operations\r\nWhat is a File and Inode?\r\nIn Linux, there is a philosophy "Everything is a file". Your pictures, texts, even your hardware\r\n(keyboard, disk) are represented as a file.\r\nInode (Index Node): It is the identity card of the file. When you create a file, two things are\r\ncreated on the disk:\r\n1. Data: The actual information inside the file.\r\n2. Inode: A record holding "metadata" such as who owns the file, its size, permissions, and\r\nwhere it resides on the disk. The file name is just a label pointing to this Inode.\r\n\r\n1. Creating Files (\r\ntouch\r\n)\r\n\r\n\fThe\r\ntouch\r\ncommand updates the timestamp if the file exists, otherwise creates an empty file.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ touch notes.txt\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -l notes.txt\r\n-rw-r--r-- 1 user user 0 Aug 01 12:00 notes.txt\r\n\r\nAs seen in the\r\nls -l\r\noutput, a file with size 0 was created.\r\nBatch Creation:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ touch file{1..3}.txt\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls\r\nfile1.txt file2.txt file3.txt\r\n\r\nUsing curly braces\r\n{}\r\n, we created 3 files in one go.\r\n\r\n2. Creating Directories (\r\nmkdir\r\n)\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ mkdir projects\r\n\r\nCreating Nested Directories (\r\n-p\r\n): Normally\r\nmkdir a/b/c\r\ngives an error because directory\r\na\r\ndoes not exist. The\r\n-p\r\n(parents) parameter creates the entire path.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ mkdir -p projects/python/app\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ tree projects\r\nprojects\r\n└── python\r\n└── app\r\n\r\n\fAs seen, even though the\r\npython\r\ndirectory didn't exist, it didn't give an error and created all of them in sequence.\r\n\r\n3. Copying (\r\ncp\r\n)\r\nCreates copies of files or directories.\r\nCommand\r\ncp file.txt backup.txt\r\ncp -r directory/\r\nbackup_directory/\r\ncp -i file.txt target/\r\n\r\ncp --backup file.txt target/\r\n\r\nDescription\r\nCopies the file.\r\nCopies the directory and its contents (Recursive).\r\nAsks before overwriting if the same file exists at target\r\n(Interactive).\r\nIf the same file exists at target, backs up the old one by\r\nrenaming (e.g.,\r\nfile.txt~\r\n).\r\n\r\nInteractive Copy (\r\n-i\r\n):\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ cp -i notes.txt /tmp/\r\ncp: overwrite '/tmp/notes.txt'? y\r\n\r\nSince there's a file with the same name, it asked us, we confirmed by saying\r\ny\r\n(yes).\r\nBackup Copy (\r\n--backup\r\n):\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ cp --backup notes.txt /tmp/\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls /tmp/notes*\r\n/tmp/notes.txt /tmp/notes.txt~\r\n\r\nIt backed up the old file by adding\r\n\r\n\f~\r\nto its name, and saved the new one with the normal name.\r\n\r\n4. Moving and Renaming (\r\nmv\r\n)\r\nThere is no "Rename" command in Linux,\r\nmv\r\n(Move) does this job.\r\n•\r\n\r\nRenaming:\r\nmv old.txt new.txt\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\nMoving:\r\nmv file.txt /tmp/\r\n\r\nExample Scenario: Moving File\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ mv notes.txt Documents/\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls Documents/\r\nnotes.txt\r\n\r\nThe file was deleted from its current location and moved to the\r\nDocuments\r\ndirectory.\r\n\r\n5. Deletion (\r\nrm\r\n)\r\nCAUTION: There is no "Recycle Bin" in Linux terminal. Deleted files are gone.\r\nCommand\r\nDescription\r\nrm file.txt\r\nDeletes the file.\r\nrm -i file.txt\r\nAsks "Are you sure?" while deleting (Safe mode).\r\nrm -r directory/ Deletes directory and its contents.\r\n\r\n\fCommand\r\nDescription\r\nrm -rf directory/ Deletes directory forcibly without asking (Very dangerous!).\r\nrmdir directory/ Deletes only empty directory (Safest method).\r\nSafe Deletion (\r\n-i\r\n):\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ rm -i important_doc.txt\r\nrm: remove regular file 'important_doc.txt'? n\r\n\r\nTo prevent accidental deletion, make it a habit to use the\r\n-i\r\nparameter.\r\nDirectory Deletion (\r\n-r\r\n):\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ rm -r projects/\r\n\r\nTo delete directories with contents,\r\n-r\r\nis mandatory.\r\n\r\n6. File Information and Inode\r\n•\r\n\r\nfile\r\n: Determines the type of file (image, text, binary).\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ file /bin/bash\r\n/bin/bash: ELF 64-bit LSB shared object, x86-64\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ file notes.txt\r\nnotes.txt: ASCII text\r\n\r\nRegardless of the extension, it tells the real content of the file.\r\n•\r\n\r\nstat\r\n: Gives very detailed information about the file (Inode, timestamps).\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ stat notes.txt\r\nFile: notes.txt\r\n\r\n\fSize: 0\r\nBlocks: 0\r\nIO Block: 4096\r\nle\r\nInode: 123456\r\nLinks: 1\r\nAccess: 2023-10-20 12:00:00.000000000 +0300\r\nModify: 2023-10-20 12:00:00.000000000 +0300\r\nChange: 2023-10-20 12:00:00.000000000 +0300\r\n\r\nregular empty fi\r\n\r\n7. File Links - Inode Concept\r\nEvery file in the Linux file system has an ID number (Inode). The file name is just a label\r\npointing to this number.\r\nTo view inodes, use\r\nls -i\r\n:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -i notes.txt\r\n123456 notes.txt\r\n\r\nHard Link\r\nGives a second name to the physical data (Inode) of the file.\r\n•\r\n•\r\n\r\nEven if the original file is deleted, data is not deleted because it is accessible via Hard\r\nLink.\r\nWorks only on the same disk partition.\r\n\r\nExample Scenario:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ln notes.txt hard_link.txt\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -li\r\n123456 -rw-r--r-- 2 user user 0 Aug 01 12:00 notes.txt\r\n123456 -rw-r--r-- 2 user user 0 Aug 01 12:00 hard_link.txt\r\n\r\nNotice, both files have the same Inode number (the number at the beginning). This means they\r\nactually point to the same data on the disk.\r\nSoft Link (Symbolic Link)\r\nLike "Shortcut" in Windows. Points only to the path of the original file.\r\n•\r\n•\r\n\r\nIf the original file is deleted, the link breaks (broken link).\r\nCan work across different disks.\r\n\r\nExample Scenario:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ln -s /var/www/html site_shortcut\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ls -li site_shortcut /var/www/html\r\n654321 drwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Aug 01 10:00 /var/www/html\r\n\r\n\f789012 lrwxrwxrwx 1 user user\r\n\r\n13 Aug 01 12:05 site_shortcut -> /var/www/html\r\n\r\nHere the Inode numbers are different.\r\nsite_shortcut\r\nis just a small file pointing to the\r\n/var/www/html\r\naddress.\r\n\r\n8. Advanced Copying (\r\ndd\r\n)\r\nThe\r\ndd\r\ncommand performs low-level copying. It's used to create or write disk images.\r\nExample: Writing ISO File to USB\r\nsudo dd if=linux.iso of=/dev/sdb bs=4M status=progress\r\n•\r\n\r\nif\r\n: Source (Input File - ISO file)\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\nof\r\n: Target (Output File - USB drive)\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\nbs\r\n: Block size (for speed).\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\nstatus=progress\r\n: Shows progress bar.\r\n\r\nSearching Files and Directories in Linux\r\n\r\n\fLinux file and directory search operations allow users to navigate efficiently across file systems.\r\nIn this section, we will discuss how to find files and directories using the\r\nfind\r\n,\r\nlocate\r\n, and\r\nwhich\r\ncommands. These commands provide suitable solutions for different scenarios and needs.\r\n\r\nfind\r\nCommand for Searching\r\nThe\r\nfind\r\ncommand is used to search for files and directories based on specific criteria. With its ability to\r\nperform in-depth searches, it produces effective results in large and complex file systems.\r\nGeneral Usage:\r\nfind [WHERE] [CRITERIA] [ACTION]\r\nBasic Searches\r\nCriteria\r\nExample Command\r\nDescription\r\nName\r\nfind / -name "notes.txt" Finds exact name "notes.txt".\r\nName (Case Insensitive) find . -iname "PiC.Jpg" Finds without caring about case.\r\nFinds only directories (\r\nd\r\nType\r\nfind /home -type d\r\n). (\r\nf\r\n: file).\r\nSize\r\nfind / -size +100M\r\nFinds files larger than 100 Megabytes.\r\nFinds files owned by\r\nUser\r\nfind /var -user www-data www-data\r\n.\r\nExample Scenario: Search by Name (\r\n-name\r\n)\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find . -name "*.txt"\r\n./Documents/notes.txt\r\n\r\n\f./Desktop/todo.txt\r\n./Downloads/list.txt\r\n./.cache/temp.txt\r\n\r\nWe listed files ending with\r\n.txt\r\nin our current directory and all subdirectories.\r\nExample Scenario: Search by Type (\r\n-type\r\n) To find only directories named\r\nssh\r\n:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find /etc -type d -name "ssh"\r\n/etc/ssh\r\n\r\nIf we hadn't specified\r\n-type d\r\n, it could have found files or links named\r\nssh\r\n.\r\nExample Scenario: Search by Size (\r\n-size\r\n) To find files larger than 1GB:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find / -size +1G\r\n/var/log/syslog.1\r\n/home/user/movie.mkv\r\n/var/lib/mysql/ibdata1\r\n\r\nThis is the most commonly used method to free up space when the disk is full.\r\nLogical Operators (AND, OR, NOT)\r\n•\r\n\r\nAND (\r\n-a\r\n): Default. Must be txt AND larger than 1MB.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find . -name "*.txt" -size +1M\r\n./large_notes.txt\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\nOR (\r\n\r\n\f-o\r\n): Jpg OR png.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find . -name "*.jpg" -o -name "*.png"\r\n./image.jpg\r\n./logo.png\r\n./screenshot.png\r\n•\r\n\r\nNOT (\r\n-not\r\n): NOT owned by root.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find . -not -user root\r\n./home/user/file.txt\r\n./tmp/test.tmp\r\n\r\nApplying Command to Found File (\r\n-exec\r\nand\r\nxargs\r\n)\r\nThis is the most powerful feature. It runs a command for every file it finds.\r\nExample: Find all\r\n.tmp\r\nfiles and delete them.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find . -name "*.tmp" -exec rm {} \\;\r\n•\r\n\r\n{}\r\n: Placeholder for the found file name.\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\n\\;\r\n: Indicates end of command.\r\n\r\nUsing xargs: When many files are found,\r\nxargs\r\nis more performant.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find . -name "*.log" | xargs rm\r\n\r\n\flocate\r\nCommand for Searching\r\nThe\r\nlocate\r\ncommand is used to find files on the system.\r\nlocate\r\nuses a database called\r\nupdatedb\r\n. This database contains an index of files on your system, and the\r\nlocate\r\ncommand searches this database quickly.\r\n•\r\n\r\nBasic Usage:\r\n\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ locate notes.txt\r\n/home/user/Documents/notes.txt\r\n/home/user/Backup/notes.txt\r\n\r\nThe\r\nlocate\r\ncommand's quick results depend on periodic updates to the file system changes by\r\nupdatedb\r\n. Therefore, it may not find very recent files. To manually update the database, you can run the\r\nsudo updatedb\r\ncommand.\r\n\r\nwhich\r\nCommand to Find Command Files\r\nThe\r\nwhich\r\ncommand is used to get information about the path of a specific command. This is especially\r\nuseful for understanding which version is being used among programs with multiple installed\r\nversions.\r\n•\r\n\r\nBasic Usage:\r\n\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ which python\r\n/usr/bin/python\r\n\r\nThis command shows where the\r\n\r\n\fpython\r\ncommand is located. This is typically used to find the location of the default\r\npython\r\nversion on the system.\r\n\r\n4. Searching INSIDE Files with\r\ngrep\r\nSearches for text inside files, not the file name.\r\nExample Scenario: Let's find lines containing "Error" in the\r\nserver.log\r\nfile.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ grep "Error" server.log\r\n[2023-10-01 10:00] Error: Connection timeout\r\n[2023-10-01 10:05] Error: Database unreachable\r\n[2023-10-01 10:10] Error: Service stopped\r\n\r\nRegex (Regular Expression) Table and Examples:\r\nSymbol Meaning\r\nExample Command Matching\r\n^\r\nStart of line\r\ngrep "^Error" log.txt "Error occurred" (Yes), "An Error" (No)\r\n$\r\nEnd of line\r\ngrep "ok$" log.txt\r\n"Process ok" (Yes), "okay" (No)\r\n.\r\nAny character\r\ngrep "c.t" words.txt cat, cut, cot\r\n*\r\nRepetition of previous grep "ab*" code.txt a, ab, abb, abbb\r\nPractical Example: Search with Regex Find lines starting with "User":\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ grep "^User" config.txt\r\nUser: admin\r\nUser: guest\r\n\r\nExample: Search in Entire Directory (\r\n-r\r\n) Search for the word "Error" in all files inside\r\n/var/log\r\n(case insensitive).\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ grep -r -i "error" /var/log/\r\n/var/log/syslog:Oct 1 12:00:00 Error: Disk full\r\n/var/log/auth.log:Oct 1 12:05:00 Failed password\r\n/var/log/kern.log:Oct 1 12:10:00 I/O Error\r\n\r\nSummary\r\n\r\n\fFile and directory search operations in Linux can be easily performed with the\r\nfind\r\n,\r\nlocate\r\n, and\r\nwhich\r\ncommands. The\r\nfind\r\ncommand is ideal for in-depth and criteria-based searches. The\r\nlocate\r\ncommand is useful when you want to get quick results but may not provide the most up-to-date\r\nresults. The\r\nwhich\r\ncommand is used specifically to find the locations of commands on the system. These tools\r\nenable Linux users to navigate effectively across file systems and find the files and programs they\r\nneed.\r\n\r\nFilters\r\nFilters are programs that take plain text (stored in a file or produced by another program) as\r\nstandard input, transform it into a meaningful format, and then return it as standard output. Linux\r\nhas a multitude of filters.\r\n\r\nWhat is Filtering and Pipe (|) Logic?\r\nIn Linux, the output of one command can be the input of another command. The mechanism\r\nproviding this is called Pipeline and is shown with the\r\n|\r\nsign.\r\nHow Does It Work? Think of it like a production line in a factory.\r\n1. Raw Material: Text read from a file.\r\n2. Machine 1 (Command 1): Reads and processes the text (E.g.,\r\ncat\r\n).\r\n3. Conveyor Belt (Pipe\r\n\r\n\f|\r\n): Carries the processed data to the next machine.\r\n4. Machine 2 (Command 2): Filters the incoming data (E.g.,\r\ngrep\r\n).\r\n5. Product: The filtered result appearing on the screen.\r\nThanks to this, commands that are simple on their own can combine to perform very complex\r\ntasks.\r\n\r\n1. Redirection\r\nIn Linux, every program has 3 doors:\r\n1. Input (STDIN - 0): Keyboard.\r\n2. Output (STDOUT - 1): Screen.\r\n3. Error (STDERR - 2): Error messages (Screen).\r\nWe can redirect these doors to files.\r\nOperator Description\r\n>\r\n\r\nWrite output to file (Deletes old content).\r\n\r\n>>\r\n2>\r\n<\r\n\r\nAppend output to end of file.\r\nSaves only errors to file.\r\nGives file as input to command.\r\nSends output of first command to second\r\n(Pipe).\r\n\r\n|\r\n\r\nExample Command and Output\r\nls > list.txt\r\n(Prints nothing to screen, writes to\r\nfile)\r\necho "Last line" >> note.txt\r\nls /nonexistent_directory 2> error.txt\r\nwc -l < list.txt\r\ncat file | grep "search"\r\n\r\nExample Scenario: Searching While Hiding Errors The\r\nfind\r\ncommand prints "Permission denied" errors for directories it cannot access. Let's get a clean\r\noutput by throwing these into the\r\n/dev/null\r\n(black hole) file.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ find / -name "secret_file" 2> /dev/null\r\n/home/admin/secret_file\r\n\r\n\f(Error messages are not visible on screen, only the found result is visible).\r\n\r\n2. Text Processing Tools\r\nLet's have an example\r\nnames.txt\r\nfile:\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ cat names.txt\r\nAli Veli\r\nAyşe Yılmaz\r\nMehmet Öz\r\nAli Veli\r\n\r\nCat\r\nThe main purpose of the Cat command is to display the contents of one or more text files in the\r\nterminal. Using this command, we can quickly view file contents.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ cat /etc/ssh/sshd_config\r\n# Port 22\r\n# AddressFamily any\r\n# ListenAddress 0.0.0.0\r\n# ListenAddress ::\r\nPermitRootLogin no\r\nPasswordAuthentication yes\r\nPermitEmptyPasswords no\r\nChallengeResponseAuthentication no\r\nUsePAM yes\r\n\r\nIn the above example, the contents of the SSH service's configuration file at\r\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config\r\nwere printed to the screen with the\r\ncat\r\ncommand.\r\nHead\r\nThe\r\nhead\r\ncommand is used to view a specific number of lines from the beginning of a specified file. By\r\ndefault, the\r\nhead\r\ncommand shows the first 10 lines of the file, but this number can be changed with the\r\n-n\r\nparameter.\r\n\r\n\fThis command is useful when you want to quickly review just the beginning of the file contents,\r\nnot the entire content.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ head -n 3 /var/log/apache2/access.log\r\n192.168.1.1 - - [15/Mar/2024:10:00:00 +0000] "GET /index.html HTTP/1.1" 200 61\r\n2 "-" "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64)"\r\n192.168.1.2 - - [15/Mar/2024:10:00:02 +0000] "POST /login.php HTTP/1.1" 200 45\r\n2 "http://example.com/login" "Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 6.0; Nexus 5 Build/M\r\nRA58N)"\r\n192.168.1.3 - - [15/Mar/2024:10:00:03 +0000] "GET /wp-admin HTTP/1.1" 403 497\r\n"-" "Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_11_6)"\r\n\r\nIn the above example, the first 3 lines of the file containing the access logs at\r\n/var/log/apache2/access.log\r\nfor Apache2 Web Server service were printed to the screen.\r\nTail\r\nThe\r\ntail\r\ncommand is used to view a specific number of lines from the end of a specified file. By default,\r\nthe\r\ntail\r\ncommand shows the last 10 lines of the file, but this number can be changed with the\r\n-n\r\nparameter.\r\nThis command is extremely useful especially for observing the most recently added content of\r\ncontinuously growing files such as log files.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ tail -n 3 /var/log/auth.log\r\nMar 15 12:00:00 servername sshd[23456]: Failed password for invalid user admin\r\nfrom 192.168.1.1 port 54321 ssh2\r\nMar 15 12:01:00 servername sshd[23457]: Accepted password for user1 from 192.1\r\n68.1.2 port 65432 ssh2\r\nMar 15 12:02:00 servername sshd[23458]: Failed password for user2 from 192.168\r\n.1.3 port 76543 ssh2\r\n\r\nIn the above example, the last three lines of the\r\nauth.log\r\nfile were printed to the screen. The\r\nauth.log\r\nfile is a log file where events related to user authentication processes are recorded in Linux\r\nsystems.\r\nLive Log Monitoring (\r\n\r\n\ftail -f\r\n): To continuously watch a log file (for example, to see incoming requests to a server in realtime), the\r\n-f\r\n(follow) parameter is used.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ tail -f /var/log/syslog\r\nAug 1 10:00:01 server CRON[123]: (root) CMD (command)\r\nAug 1 10:05:01 server sshd[456]: Accepted password for user...\r\n\r\n(The screen flows as new logs arrive. Press\r\nCTRL+C\r\nto exit).\r\nSort\r\nThe\r\nsort\r\ncommand sorts the contents of the given file alphabetically.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ cat names.txt\r\nBob\r\nCharlie\r\nAlice\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ sort names.txt\r\nAlice\r\nBob\r\nCharlie\r\n\r\nIn the above example, we printed the names in "names.txt" to the screen "alphabetically".\r\nUniq\r\nThe\r\nuniq\r\ncommand filters consecutively repeating lines and shows unique lines in the file.\r\nIt is generally used together with the\r\nsort\r\ncommand because when used alone, it only detects consecutively repeating lines.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ cat names.txt\r\nAlice\r\nCharlie\r\nAlice\r\nBob\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ sort names.txt | uniq\r\n\r\n\fAlice\r\nBob\r\nCharlie\r\n•\r\n\r\n-c\r\n: Shows the count of repetitions (Count).\r\n\r\nExample: Let's count how many of each name there are\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ sort names.txt | uniq -c\r\n2 Ali Veli\r\n1 Ayşe Yılmaz\r\n1 Mehmet Öz\r\n\r\nGrep\r\nThe\r\ngrep\r\ncommand is used to search for specific text strings in files, filter lines, and display matching\r\nresults.\r\ngrep\r\nis a very powerful tool and is frequently used for searches on log files, configuration files, or any\r\ntext file.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ grep '192.168.1.1' /var/log/apache2/access.log\r\n192.168.1.1 - - [15/Mar/2024:10:00:00 +0000] "GET /index.html HTTP/1.1" 200 61\r\n2 "-" "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64)"\r\n192.168.1.1 - - [15/Mar/2024:10:00:02 +0000] "POST /login.php HTTP/1.1" 200 45\r\n2 "http://example.com/login" "Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 6.0; Nexus 5 Build/M\r\nRA58N)"\r\n192.168.1.1 - - [15/Mar/2024:10:00:03 +0000] "GET /wp-admin HTTP/1.1" 403 497\r\n"-" "Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_11_6)"\r\n\r\nThis command will print only the records with IP address\r\n192.168.1.1\r\nto the screen from the access logs of the Apache 2 web server.\r\nAdvanced\r\ngrep\r\nParameters:\r\n•\r\n\r\n-i\r\n: Case insensitive.\r\n\r\n•\r\n\r\n-v\r\n\r\n\f: Show non-matching (exclude).\r\n•\r\n\r\n-r\r\n: Recursive search in directory.\r\n\r\nWc\r\nThe\r\nwc\r\n(word count) command allows you to quickly understand how large files are or how much data\r\nthey contain.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ wc /etc/passwd\r\n46\r\n67 2544 /etc/passwd\r\n\r\nIn the above example, the\r\nwc\r\ncommand returned the line count, word count, and total character count of the\r\n/etc/passwd\r\nfile, which contains the list of registered users in Linux operating systems.\r\nColumn value Description\r\n46\r\nLine count\r\n67\r\nWord count\r\n2544\r\nCharacter count\r\n/etc/passwd\r\nFile path\r\nCut\r\nSplits lines and takes the column you want. The\r\n/etc/passwd\r\nfile is the best example for this.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ cut -d ":" -f 1 /etc/passwd | head -n 3\r\nroot\r\ndaemon\r\nbin\r\n\r\n(\r\n-d\r\n: Delimiter character [:],\r\n-f\r\n: Field number [1]).\r\n\r\n\fAwk\r\nThe\r\nawk\r\ncommand is designed for text and data processing tasks and is quite effective especially when\r\nworking with column-based data. It reads files line by line, divides each line into fields\r\n(columns), and processes according to specified conditions.\r\nawk\r\noffers many functions and control structures for complex text operations.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ cat names.txt\r\nJohn Doe\r\nEmily Clark\r\nAlex Turner\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ awk '{print $1}' names.txt\r\nJohn\r\nEmily\r\nAlex\r\n\r\nIn this example, there are three first name-last name pairs in a file named\r\nnames.txt\r\n: John Doe, Emily Clark, and Alex Turner. The command\r\nawk '{print $1}' names.txt\r\nprocesses the contents of this file using the\r\nawk\r\nprogram.\r\nawk\r\nreads text files line by line and divides each line into fields based on space or tab characters. In\r\nthis example, the expression\r\n{print $1}\r\ninstructs to print the first field of each line (i.e., the first name).\r\nAdvanced Example: Process List Let's get only the User Name ($1) and Command ($11)\r\ncolumns from the\r\nps aux\r\noutput.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ ps aux | awk '{print $1, $11}' | head -n 3\r\nUSER COMMAND\r\nroot /sbin/init\r\nroot [kthreadd]\r\n\r\nSed\r\nThe\r\nsed\r\n\r\n\f(stream editor) command is a tool that can perform various text edits such as processing,\r\nreplacing, adding, deleting text, or replacing between files.\r\nThe\r\nsed\r\ncommand is generally used to filter and transform texts.\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ cat names.txt\r\nAlice\r\nCharlie\r\nBob\r\nroot@hackerbox:~$ sed 's/Alice/George/' names.txt\r\nGeorge\r\nCharlie\r\nBob\r\n\r\nIn the above example, the name Alice in\r\nnames.txt\r\nwas changed to George with the help of the\r\nsed\r\ncommand. However, the\r\nsed\r\ncommand did not make changes to the file, only printed the newly made change to the screen. To\r\npermanently change the file, the\r\n-i\r\nparameter is used.\r\nTee\r\nPrints output both to screen and writes to file.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ echo "Log Entry" | tee log.txt\r\nLog Entry\r\n\r\nDiff\r\nShows differences between two files.\r\nuser@hackerbox:~$ diff file1.txt file2.txt\r\n< Old line\r\n> New line\r\n\r\nTr\r\nPerforms character replacement.\r\nExample: Let's make lowercase letters uppercase\r\n\r\n\fuser@hackerbox:~$ echo "hello" | tr "a-z" "A-Z"\r\nHELLO\r\n\r\n\f	'+0000':4280,4298,4321,4766,4784,4807 '+0300':2686,2694,2702 '+1':3238,3280 '+100':3135 '-01':3567,3575,3583 '-10':2681,2689,2697,3566,3574,3582 '-20':2682,2690,2698 '-64':2631 '/.bashrc':629,653 '/.cache/temp.txt':3171 '/bin':755 '/bin/bash':300,313,977,991,2622,2623 '/desktop/todo.txt':3169 '/dev/null':4080,4091 '/dev/sdb':2976 '/documents':1882 '/documents/notes.txt':3168 '/downloads':1885 '/downloads/list.txt':3170 '/etc':1268,1332,1335,1345,3200 '/etc/passwd':441,4887,4891,4911,4936,4949,4963 '/etc/ssh':3205 '/etc/ssh/sshd_config'