8,2679,2718,2736,2763,2854,2864,2924,2986,3045,3209,3224,3250,3358,3379,3396,3575,3619,3646,3688,3778,3795,3867,3877,3938,3999,4022,4026,4040,4342,4440,4446,4891,5561,6806,6812,6825,6956,7260,7269,7372,7401 'websit':74,262,274,328,336,376,402,425,451,478,554,748,891,966,980,990,1024,1076,1088,1101,1109,1114,1148,1154,1173,1200,1210,1497,1540,1553,1578,1593,1612,1639,1671,1700,1745,1801,1814,1839,1854,1873,1898,1911,1916,2024,2065,2094,2132,2159,2196,2381,2409,2618,2873,3049,3091,3149,3173,3280,3296,3312,3366,3455,3468,3478,3490,3530,3716,3983,3986,3992,4009,4044,4132,4148,4228,4249,4267,4297,4351,4359,4369,4382,4404,4407,4454,4529,4532,4582,4685,4700,4729,4998,5150,5216,5328,5668,5735,6242,6304,6375,6396,6452,6464,6488,6549,6830,6882,7002,7130,7267,7287,7378,7381,7417,7425,7434,7555 'week':2907,6221,6254,6269,6907 'weight':1191 'well':440,658 'went':629 'wide':4303,5123 'win':2714 'wise':3634,5555 'within':3644,3914,4023 'without':2600,2805 'word':3633 'work':42,782,1405,1659,1791 'world':4302 'wors':3391 'worth':4274,5786,5981,6061 'would':1508,2332,6000,6725 'write':2967,2973,3186,6919,7020 'www.google.com':7674 'www.google.com/finance?q=nasdaq%3agoog':7673 'www.mediabistro.com':7667 'www.mediabistro.com/alltwitter/files/2011/06/internet-60-seconds-infographic.jpg':7666 'www.quora.com':7670 'www.quora.com/what-percentage-of-people-who-click-on-google-search-ads-understand-the-differencebetween-ads-and-organic-results':7669 'www.searchengineland.com':7150 'www.seobook.com':7146 'www.seomoz.com':7144 'www.seomoz.org':7682 'www.seomoz.org/article/search-ranking-factors':7681 'www.seroundtable.com':7148 'yahoo':1037 'year':4832,5084 'yellow':631 'yes':471 'yet':4072,5019 'york':1204
12	4	Ethics expose		Ethics	t	C:\\xampp\\htdocs\\Public_library_codebase\\storage\\uploads\\documents\\4\\de0f28b4de1d866309ccbfc695d28b26.pdf	\N	2026-04-28 19:54:53.930808	HAPPINESS IN THE AFRICAN\r\nTRADITION VS IN THE WEST\r\nCourse: Ethics and Development\r\n\r\nBachelor’s 2 in Conpetion and Design of Applications for the Digital Economy\r\n\r\nMembers:\r\n\r\n• Kenvo Fomazou Samuel\r\n• Tsehoule Ngalock Blondel\r\n• Tchatchou Tchatchou Moise\r\n• Kemdem Tatchim Adrien\r\n\r\nDecember 2025\r\n\r\nCourse Supervisor\r\n\r\nFather Matthieu De La Croix\r\n\r\n\fAbstract\r\nThis work is an exposé in of Bachelor’s 2 students of Saint Jean Ingénier under\r\nthe course “Ethique et Dévélopement”. Our supervisor is Pere Mathieu De La\r\nCroix.\r\nWe will answer two questions in this work:\r\n1. The comparism between the African model of happiness and the\r\nWestern individualistic view\r\n2. How the community contributes to the happiness in the African society.\r\n\r\n\fContents\r\nAbstract............................................................................................... 0\r\n“Comparez le modèle africain du bonheur avec une conception\r\noccidentale individualiste.” ................................................................. 3\r\nIndividualism vs Collectivism............................................................... 3\r\nAttributes defining individualism and collectivism.............................. 3\r\n“Comment la communauté contribue-t-elle au bonheur dans les\r\ntraditions africaines ?” ........................................................................ 4\r\nCase study: Mami Koki .................................................................... 4\r\nCase study: Water scarcity ............................................................... 4\r\nBibliography ........................................................................................ 5\r\n\r\n\f“Comparez le modèle africain du bonheur avec une\r\nconception occidentale individualiste.”\r\nThrough centuries, humans have gone a long way; from discovering fire, inventing the plane,\r\nand even going to the moon. All these breakthroughs have created immense joy among the\r\nhuman race. But yet, we as a kind have not stopped to seek for more. It becomes obvious that\r\nhumans are always on a quest for something bigger.\r\nHowever, people across poles and hemispheres seem to have fundamentally opposing views\r\nas of what is happiness. Throughout this exposé, I’ll compare the concept of happiness in the\r\nWest and in Africa.\r\n\r\nIndividualism vs Collectivism\r\nWhen analysing the Western and the African views of happiness, two major doctrines stand\r\nout:\r\nIndividualism: A tendency for a person to act without reference to others\r\nCollectivism: A culture in which people view themselves as a group rather than individuals.\r\nIn collectivistic cultures, child rearing emphasizes conformity, obedience, security, and\r\nreliability. Collectivistic parents teach their children the importance of family lineage and\r\nancestry. Typically, the father dominates the collectivist’s home, where rank in the family is\r\noften determined by sex and age.\r\n\r\nAttributes defining individualism and collectivism\r\nHarry Triandis, from the University of Illinois, is well known for his work on individualism\r\nand collectivism. Triandis discusses four defining attributes of individualism–collectivism:\r\n1. How individuals perceive themselves (e.g., “I am distinct and unique” vs. “I am a\r\nmember of a family, tribe”)\r\n2. How individuals relate to others (e.g., “How/what do I gain from this act?” vs. “How\r\nwill this act affect others?”)\r\n3. The goals they follow (e.g., “I want to win” vs. “I’m a team player to help the group win”)\r\n4. What drives their behaviour (e.g., “It is my right to do this” vs. “My duty is to my group”)\r\n\r\n\f“Comment la communauté contribue-t-elle au bonheur dans\r\nles traditions africaines ?”\r\nAfrican societies stand out in terms of the way of life. The following are some traits that\r\nillustrate collectivism in African societies.\r\n1. Each other’s keeper\r\nAfrica has in its history been made up of communities, in turn made up of families,\r\nfundamental level of the social pyramid. Raising a child in such an environment is often a\r\ncollective effort rather than just a ‘father and mother’ effort.\r\n\r\nCase study: Mami Koki\r\nJoel is a child in Douala, his mother is known for inviting her neighbours home during feasts.\r\nShe has even earned the nickname, ‘Mami Koki’. On a Friday after school, Joel has an\r\naccident with his bicycle, he is rushed to the hospital by his mother. Joel can’t receive\r\ntreatment because of the high bill. Joel’s absence for several days doesn’t go unnoticed by his\r\nneighbours. They hear of Joel’s condition and immediately start a fundraising for him. Soon\r\nJoel receives the funds and recovers.\r\n\r\n2. “All for one and one for all”\r\nThough this aspect is declining in newer generations, it is very much present in our daily\r\nlives. It’s mostly about solidarity among people.\r\n\r\nCase study: Water scarcity\r\nIn the Nsimalen neighbourhood, people had to walk long distances in order to get potable\r\nwater. To solve this issue, the members of the neighbourhood agreed to contribute in order to\r\ndig a well. Some gave cash while assisted in the digging of the well.\r\n\r\nCase study: Short ride gone wrong\r\nTchatchou is a university student. On a Saturday evening he takes his father’s car for a short\r\nride. On his way back, he misses a turn and has one tire stuck a in a gutter. He gets out of the\r\ncar panicking, not knowing what he’ll tell his dad. Then luck strikes, bystanders who watched\r\nthe scene come and help hip push the car out of the gutter. Tchatchou is both dumbfounded\r\nand relieved as the people leave without asking for any money.\r\n\r\n\fBibliography\r\n1. Pirttilä-Backman, A. M., Kassea, B. R., & Ikonen, T. (2004). Cameroonian Forms of\r\nCollectivism and Individ- ualism. Journal of Cross-Cultural Psychology\r\n2. Joshanloo, Mohsen (21 March 2013). "Eastern Conceptualizations of Happiness:\r\nFundamental Differences with Western Views".\r\n\r\n\f	'0':115 '1':87,382,499,812 '2':16,59,101,402,639,837 '2004':823 '2013':842 '2025':41 '21':840 '3':127,131,137,423 '4':151,156,161,444 '5':163 'absenc':608 'abstract':49,114 'accid':583 'across':234 'act':290,415,420 'adrien':39 'affect':421 'africa':264,504 'africain':119,150,167,476 'african':4,92,111,274,477,497 'age':351 'agre':700 'alway':225 'among':202,669 'analys':269 'ancestri':331 'answer':81 'applic':22 'ask':807 'aspect':649 'assist':713 'attribut':132,352,378 'au':145,471 'avec':122,170 'b':819 'bachelor':14,57 'back':748 'backman':815 'becom':220 'behaviour':448 'bibliographi':162,811 'bicycl':586 'bigger':231 'bill':605 'blondel':33 'bonheur':121,146,169,472 'breakthrough':197 'bystand':780 'cameroonian':824 'car':740,767,791 'case':152,157,546,671,720 'cash':711 'centuri':176 'child':312,528,553 'children':324 'collect':536 'collectiv':130,136,267,295,356,373,381,495,827 'collectivist':310,320,337 'come':785 'comment':138,464 'communauté':140,466 'communiti':104,513 'compar':89,254 'comparez':116,164 'concept':124,172,256 'conceptu':844 'condit':624 'conform':315 'conpet':18 'content':113 'contribu':142,468 'contribue-t-ell':141,467 'contribut':105,702 'cours':10,42,67 'creat':199 'croix':48,78 'cross':834 'cross-cultur':833 'cultur':297,311,835 'dad':776 'daili':662 'dan':147,473 'day':611 'de':46,76 'decemb':40 'declin':651 'defin':133,353,377 'design':20 'determin':347 'develop':13 'differ':848 'dig':706,716 'digit':25 'discov':184 'discuss':375 'distanc':684 'distinct':390 'doctrin':280 'doesn':612 'domin':335 'douala':555 'drive':446 'du':120,168 'dumbfound':799 'duti':459 'dévélopement':70 'e.g':387,408,428,449 'earn':570 'eastern':843 'economi':26 'effort':537,545 'ell':144,470 'emphas':314 'environ':532 'et'